 Pathanamthitta (1.707), while for the Christians the respective districts are Kasaragod (1.929) and Kollam (1.539).<ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/F-series/f10/2011-F10-32-MDDS.XLS</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Non-Municipal Census Towns in Kerala]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Topics related to Kerala}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Demographics Of Kerala}}\n[[Category:Kerala society|*]]\n[[Category:Demographics of India by state or union territory]]\n[[Category:Kerala-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[Kerala]] is a state in south-western India. Most of Kerala's 34.8&nbsp;million people (in 2011) are on of [[Malayali]] ([[Malayalam language]] speaking) ethnicity. Most of the Malayalam and English speaking Keralites derive their ancestry from [[Dravidian people|Dravidian]] communities that settled in Kerala. Additional ancestries derive from several centuries of contact with non-Indian lands, whereby people of [[Arab]], [[Jew]]ish, and other ethnicities settled in Kerala. Many of these immigrants [[miscegenation|intermarried]] with native Malayalam speakers resulting in formation of many Christians and Muslims in Kerala.<ref>Western Influence on Malayalam Language and Literature by K. M. George, p2, {{ISBN|81-260-0413-4}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=MZqqyxVkufQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Western+Influence+on+Malayalam+Language+and+Literature#PPA2,M1 Google book]</ref><ref>Caste, Class and Catholicism in India 1789-1914 by Kenneth Ballhatchet, p2, {{ISBN|0-7007-1095-7}}</ref> A tiny number of Muslims thus take lineage from Arab settlers mixed with local population.\n\n[[Malayalam]] is Kerala's [[official language]] and is spoken by at least 96% of the people of Kerala; the next most common languages are [[English language|English]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]], spoken mainly by [[Migrant labourers in Kerala|migrant]] workers from North and eastern parts of India and also from the neighbouring state of Tamil Nadu. [[Tulu language|Tulu]] and [[Kannada]] is spoken in most parts of the northern district of Kasaragod, adjoining [[Karnataka]]. In addition, Kerala is home to 321,000 indigenous tribal ''[[Adivasi]]s'' (1.10% of the populace).<ref name=\"Kalathil_2004_10\">{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|p=10}}.</ref> Some 63% of tribals reside in the eastern districts of Wayanad (where 35.82% are tribals), Palakkad (1.02%), and Idukki (15.66%).<ref name=\"Kalathil_2004_12\">{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|p=12}}.</ref> These groups, including the Irulars, [[Kurumbar]]s, and Mudugars,<ref>{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|pp=13\u201314}}.</ref> speak their own native languages.<ref name=\"Kalathil_2004_30-32\">{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|pp=30\u201332}}.</ref><ref name=\"Kalathil_2004_37\">{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|p=37}}.</ref><ref name=\"Kalathil_2004_39\">{{Harv|Kalathil|2004|p=39}}.</ref> [[Cholanaikkan]] tribe in the [[Silent Valley National Park]] were [[First contact (anthropology)|contacted]] only in the 1970s and they are the most isolated tribe in the state.\n\n==Population==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; font-size:85%; width:175px; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#33c; color:white;\"| '''Population density of Kerala'''\n|-  style=\"background:#fff; color:#555; text-align:center;\"\n| [[File:Kerala density map1.PNG|center|175px|Kerala's districts, shaded by population density (inhabitants per km\u00b2.]]<div style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align:justify\"><center>Kerala's districts, shaded by population density.</center></div>\n|-  style=\"background:#eee; color:black; text-align:center;\"\n| Source: {{Harv|GOK|2001}}.\n|}\n\nKerala is home to 2.76% of India's people, and &mdash; at 859 persons per km\u00b2;<ref name=\"Census 2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_results_paper1_india.html |title=Census of India : Provisional Population Totals India : Paper1 : Census 2011 |publisher=Censusindia.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref> its land is three times as densely settled as the rest of India. However, Kerala's [[population growth rate]] is far lower than the national average. Whereas Kerala's population more than doubled between 1951 and 1991 &mdash; adding 15.6&nbsp;million people to reach a total of 29.1&nbsp;million residents in 1991 &mdash; the population stood at 31.8 million by 2001 and 33.3 million in 2011.<ref name=\"Census 2011\"/> Kerala's people are most densely settled in the coastal region, leaving the eastern hills and mountains comparatively sparsely populated.<ref name=\"GOK_2005b\">{{Harv|GOK|2005b}}.</ref>\n\n[[Hinduism]] is followed by the majority of Keralites (54.7%). The major religions followed in Kerala are [[Hinduism]] (54.7% \u2014 [[Hinduism of Kerala]]), [[Islam]] (26.6%) and [[Christianity]] (18.4%).<ref name=\"Indian Census\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/|title=Indian Census|publisher=Censusindia.gov.in|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nKerala also had a [[Cochin Jews|tiny Jewish population]] until recently, said to date from 587 BC when they fled the occupation of [[Jerusalem]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II of Babylon|Nebuchadnezzar]].<ref>[http://ednafernandes.com/ Edna Fernandes], The Last Jews of Kerala, Skyhorse Publishing, 2008</ref> The 2001 Indian census recorded only 51 Jews in Kerala. The [[Paradesi Synagogue|synagogue]] in [[Kochi, India|Kochi]] is the oldest in the [[Commonwealth of Nations]].\n\nThe state has many famous [[temples]], [[mosques]], and [[church (building)|churches]]. The oldest church in India is found in Kerala, believed to be established by St. Thomas the disciple of Jesus Christ.\n\n== Features ==\n===Social development===\nKerala ranks highest in India with respect to social development indices such as elimination of poverty, primary [[education]] and healthcare. This resulted from significant efforts begun in 1911 by the erstwhile [[Kingdom of Cochin|Princely states of Cochin]] and [[Travancore]] to boost healthcare and education among the people and aided by the Christian missionaries.  This central focus &mdash; unusual in India &mdash; was then maintained after Kerala's post-independence inauguration as a state.<ref name=\"Varma_2005\">{{Harv|Varma|2005}}.</ref> Thus, Kerala has the highest literacy rate in India of 93.91% (2011);<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/india/Final_PPT_2011_chapter6.pdf/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903062239/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/india/Final_PPT_2011_chapter6.pdf/ |date=3 September 2013 }}</ref> and life expectancy is now the highest in India.The suicide rates in Kerala are the highest in India.<ref> http://ncrb.nic.in/StatPublications/ADSI/ADSI2015/chapter-2%2520suicides-v1.pdf&ved=0ahUKEwibmOS41p_XAhUBLo8KHVjhCeUQFgh7MAk&usg=AOvVaw1qQ89yX7CZ0QKT6J9VigMn </ref> As per the 2011 census, Kerala and Puducherry are the only states in India with a [[sex ratio|female-to-male ratio]] higher than 0.99. The ratio for Kerala is 1.084 &mdash; 1084 females per 1000 males &mdash; while the national figure is 0.940.<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-Common/CensusData2011.html|title=Census of India Website : Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in}}</ref> It is also one of the states in India to have [[sub-replacement fertility]].<ref> http://niti.gov.in/content/total-fertility-rate-tfr-birth-woman.</ref> [[UNICEF]] and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) designated Kerala the world's first \"baby-friendly state\" via its \"[[Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative]]\". The state is also known for [[Ayurveda]], a traditional system of [[medicine]] &mdash; this traditional expertise is currently drawing increasing numbers of [[Medical tourism|medical tourist]]s. However, drawbacks to this situation includes the population's steady aging &mdash; indeed, 11.2% of Keralites are age 60 or over.<ref name=\"Varma_2005\" />\n\nKerala's unusual socioeconomic and demographic situation was summarized by [[author]] and [[environmentalism|environmentalist]] [[Bill McKibben]]:<ref name=\"McKibben_2006\">{{Harv|McKibben|2006}}.</ref>\n\n===Emigration===\nAs of 2011, a total of 2,280,000 Keralites reside outside India. Largest populations are found in UAE (883,313) and USA (680,076).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=127311 |title=Migration From Kerala Growing Steadily, Shows Study |publisher=Daijiworld.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2011, the major concentrations of expat Keralites are in the following nations:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/a-gulf-without-keralites-could-soon-be-a-reality-2012-10-18-1.479297 |title=A Gulf without Keralites could soon be a reality |publisher=Emirates 24/7 |date=2012-10-18 |accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref>\n\n* [[UAE]] - 883,313\n* [[United States]] - 680,076 (mainly U.S. Citizens)\n* [[KSA]] - 574,739\n* [[Oman]] - 195,300\n* [[Qatar]] - 410,000\n* [[Kuwait]] - 127,782\n* [[Bahrain]] - 216,000\n* [[United Kingdom]] - 44,640\n* [[Canada]] - 28,000\n* [[Australia]] - 50,000\n* [[Portugal]] - 2,000\n* [[Italy]] - 25,000\n* [[Germany]] - 10,000\n\n===Diversity===\nThere are more than 2,500,000 migrants living in Kerala,<ref name=\"frontlineonnet.com\">[http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2801/stories/20110114280104400.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131141042/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2801/stories/20110114280104400.htm |date=31 January 2011 }}</ref> mostly from [[Assam]] and [[West Bengal]], constituting more than 8% of the population. There are also migrants from Bihar, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, and the North East.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/in-migrants-own-country/821311/0 |title=In Migrants\u2019 Own Country |publisher=Indian Express |date=2011-07-24 |accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref> In some places like [[Perumbavoor]] and [[Attingal]] they outnumber the locals.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1080810/jsp/7days/story_9671372.jsp | location=Kolkata, India | work=The Telegraph | title=No Malayalam please, we're Bongs | date=10 August 2008}}</ref> Some alarmists have even written that \"of late, Kerala has been hearing more [[Bengali language|Bengali]] than its own local language\",<ref>[http://www.premiuminvestments.in/corporate-inklings/57556p104/57503.html] {{Dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> which is a huge exaggeration, since there are very few migrants in Northern Kerala. Most of the migrants tend to concentrate around central and southern Kerala, especially in [[Kochi]] and [[Trivandrum]] (Notable exception would be [[Kozhikode]]. In Kozhikode, northern immigrants constitute more than 8% of the total population, at 35,000).<ref name=\"frontlineonnet.com\"/> In [[Kochi]] that percentage is 34% and in [[Trivandrum]] it is 30%.\n\nStudies indicate that by the time of [[Elections in Kerala|2016 state elections]], migrants will become a crucial voting block in many of the constituencies in Thiruvananthapuram, Kochi, Kozhikode, Thrissur and Kannur.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110420/jsp/nation/story_13877410.jsp | location=Kolkata, India | work=The Telegraph | first=K.M. | last=Rakesh | title=Missing voters | date=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Lists==\n\n===Class I cities===\nKerala has six major cities: [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kochi]], [[Kozhikode]], [[Kollam]], [[Thrissur]] and [[Kannur]]. Over a third of Keralites live in these large cities (a higher percentage than any other state), and over half the population lives in urban centres.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-10-28/india/30332125_1_million-plus-cities-big-city-urban-population | work=The Times Of India | title=One in 3 Keralites lives in big cities | date=28 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{Major cities in Kerala}}\n\nAccording to World Gazetteer<ref name=\"WG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=80&geo=-104&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&msz=1500&va=&pt=a |title=India: metropolitan areas |publisher=World Gazetteer |accessdate=17 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221223114/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=80&geo=-104&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&msz=1500&va=&pt=a |archivedate=21 December 2008 }}</ref> population calculation for the year 2010, five of the top 100 most populous metropolitan areas in India belong to Kerala. They are '''Kochi, Thiruvananthapuram, Kozhikode, Kannur''' and '''Kollam''' ranking 26, 43, 46, 73 and 86 respectively.\n\n===Most populous urban agglomerations===\n<!--\"List of most populous urban agglomerations in Kerala\" redirects here-->\nThe following is a list of most populous [[urban agglomeration]]s in the [[Kerala]] state of India. Population statistics indicated in this article as of 2011 census.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/towns/ker_towns.pdf |title=ALPHABETICAL LIST OF TOWNS AND THEIR POPULATION }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2-vol2/data_files/kerala/Analysis_Census_Data.pdf|title= Population Analysis with list of UAs and their Population}}</ref><ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2-vol2/data_files/kerala/Analysis_Census_Data.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2-vol2/data_files/kerala/Analysis_Census_Data.pdf |format=PDF |title=Analysis of Census Date : 2011 |publisher=Censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=2015-05-20}}</ref> Note that this is a list of metropolitan population and does not indicate the city populations. For that, see [[List of most populous cities in India]].\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"width: 50%; font-size: 0.90em;\"\n|-\n! Rank !! UA !! Population (2011) !! Po