ef>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/F-series/f10/2011-F10-32-MDDS.XLS</ref>\n\nFor Hindus, the TFR is highest in Wayanad (1.710) and lowest in Thiruvananthapuram (1.435). For the Muslims, it is Kannur (2.779) and Pathanamthitta (1.707), while for the Christians the respective districts are Kasaragod (1.929) and Kollam (1.539).<ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/F-series/f10/2011-F10-32-MDDS.XLS</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Non-Municipal Census Towns in Kerala]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Topics related to Kerala}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Demographics Of Kerala}}\n[[Category:Kerala society|*]]\n[[Category:Demographics of India by state or union territory]]\n[[Category:Kerala-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Aditya1917", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor Change- Separated titles as they were easy to read", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_Kerala"}
{"title_page": "Hidetaka Miyazaki", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese video game director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hidetaka Miyazaki\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| native_name        = \u5bae\u5d0e \u82f1\u9ad8\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date|mos=1|29|2004}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka]], Japan\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| alma_mater         = [[Keio University]]\n| occupation         = [[Creative director|Game director]], [[game designer]], writer\n| notable_works      = {{ubl|''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series|''[[Bloodborne]]''|''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''}}\n| title              = [[President (corporate title)|President]] of [[FromSoftware|FromSoftware, Inc.]]\n| term               = 2014\u2013present\n| awards             = {{ubl|Lifetime Achievement|([[2018 Golden Joystick Awards]])}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Hidetaka Miyazaki'''|\u5bae\u5d0e \u82f1\u9ad8|Miyazaki Hidetaka|born in [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka]], Japan}} is a Japanese [[Creative director|video game director]], designer, writer, and company [[President (corporate title)|president]] of [[FromSoftware]]. He originally joined them in 2004 as a game designer for the ''[[Armored Core]]'' series, and soon became internationally known for directing the ''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series, starting with ''[[Demon's Souls]]'' in 2009. Other notable games he has directed include ''[[Bloodborne]]'' and ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.\n\nMiyazaki's influences range from the works of various novelists, [[mangaka]]s, and other [[game designer]]s such as [[Fumito Ueda]] and [[Yuji Horii]], as well as Asian and European architecture. Miyazaki's games, particularly the ''Souls'' series, often invoke the use of [[Degree of difficulty#In video gaming|high difficulty]], strong [[visual storytelling|visual and environmental storytelling]], and a large amount of [[Setting (narrative)|setting]] and character background information provided through mostly vague [[flavor text]] and [[Fluff (fiction)|fluff]]. His work in the ''Souls'' series has been seen as influential, with him winning awards and being cited as an [[auteur]] of video games.\n\n==Early life==\nMiyazaki grew up \"tremendously poor\" while living in the city of [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka, Japan]], stating that he had no life ambitions as a child unlike many peers at that age.<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Parkin|first1=Simon|title=Bloodborne creator Hidetaka Miyazaki: \u2018I didn\u2019t have a dream. I wasn\u2019t ambitious'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 8, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603192210/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> Despite that, he was a heavy reader, but as his parents could not afford to buy him books or [[manga]], he had to borrow from his local library.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> The books he read at the time, many in English, were sometimes beyond his reading capabilities, with parts he could not fully understand. Using his imagination to fill in the blanks by using the accompanying illustrations, Miyazaki used this as inspiration for some of his later ideas on [[video game design]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Alongside this, he was restricted from playing video games by his parents until he was old enough to attend university, so he instead played [[gamebook]]s and [[tabletop game]]s such as ''[[Steve Jackson's Sorcery!]]'' and ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.<ref name=\"IGNinterview\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from [[Keio University]] with a degree in [[social science]], Miyazaki went to work doing [[account managing]] for the US based [[Oracle Corporation]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/><ref name=\"andriasang\">{{cite web|last1=Gantayat|first1=Anoop|title=Hidetaka Miyazaki Discusses Dark Souls|url=http://andriasang.com/comttl/miyazaki_dark_souls/|accessdate=April 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427103144/http://andriasang.com/comttl/miyazaki_dark_souls/ |archivedate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Upon a friend's recommendation, Miyazaki began playing the 2001 video game ''[[Ico]]'', causing him to consider a career change to a game designer.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> At age 29 however, Miyazaki found that few game companies would employ him, with one of the few being [[FromSoftware]], where Miyazaki began working as a game planner on ''[[Armored Core: Last Raven]]'' in 2004, joining the game's development halfway through.<ref name=\"Interview\"/><ref name=\"andriasang\"/> Miyazaki later directed ''[[Armored Core 4]]'' and its direct sequel, ''[[Armored Core: For Answer]]''.<ref name=\"andriasang\"/>\n\nUpon learning about what later became ''[[Demon's Souls]]'', Miyazaki became excited at the prospect of a fantasy [[action role-playing game]] and offered to help.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> The project, up until Miyazaki was assigned to it, was considered a failure by the company, with Miyazaki stating \"I figured if I could find a way to take control of the game, I could turn it into anything I wanted. Best of all, if my ideas failed, nobody would care \u2013 it was already a failure.\"<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Although the game was received negatively at the 2009 [[Tokyo Game Show]] and sold far under expectations upon release, it began to pick up after a few months and soon found publishers willing to release the title outside of Japan.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> After the release and success of the game's [[spiritual successor]] ''[[Dark Souls]]'' in 2011, Miyazaki was promoted to the position of company president in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duwell|first1=Ron|title=Dark Souls\u2019 Hidetaka Miyazaki Promoted to President of From Software|url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/05/22/dark-souls-hidetaka-miyazaki-promoted-to-president-of-from-software/|publisher=Techno Buffalo|accessdate=March 25, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402192158/http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/05/22/dark-souls-hidetaka-miyazaki-promoted-to-president-of-from-software/|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Karmali|first1=Luke|title=Dark Souls Director Hidetaka Miyazaki Made President of From Software|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/21/dark-souls-director-hidetaka-miyazaki-made-from-software-president|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=June 10, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524103505/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/21/dark-souls-director-hidetaka-miyazaki-made-from-software-president|archivedate=May 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the release of the ''Prepare to Die'' edition of ''Dark Souls'' in August 2012, [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] approached FromSoftware concerning cooperative development on a new title. Miyazaki asked about the possibility of developing a game for [[History of video game consoles (eighth generation)|eighth-generation consoles]], and the concept of ''[[Bloodborne]]'' developed from there. There were no story or setting connections to FromSoftware's previous games, even though Miyazaki conceded that it carried the \"DNA\" of ''Demon's Souls'' and its specific level design.<ref name= \"IGNinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/02/05/inside-the-mind-of-bloodborne-and-dark-souls-creator-ign-first|title=Inside the Mind of Bloodborne and Dark Souls' Creator \u2013 IGN First|last=Silva|first=Marty|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=February 5, 2015|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref> Development ran parallel to that of ''Dark Souls II'', which Miyazaki supervised only as he was unable to direct both games simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/260/G026038/20140611091/|title=\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30cf\u30fc\u30c9\u3067\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u3092\u2015\u2015PS4\u5c02\u7528\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u300cBloodborne\uff08\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30c9\u30dc\u30fc\u30f3\uff09\u300d\u3068\u306f\u3069\u3093\u306a\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u306a\u306e\u304b\u3002\u30c7\u30a3\u30ec\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30fb\u5bae\u5d0e\u82f1\u9ad8\u6c0f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|language=Japanese|publisher=4Gamer|date=June 19, 2014|accessdate=February 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216122013/http://www.4gamer.net/games/260/G026038/20140611091/|archivedate=February 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the release of ''Bloodborne'' in March 2015, Miyazaki returned to the ''Souls'' series as the director on ''[[Dark Souls III]]'' (2016), with assistance from ''[[Steel Battalion: Heavy Armor]]'' and ''[[Dark Souls II]]'' directors Isamu Okano and Yui Tanimura, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 is Directed by Hidetaka Miyazaki|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-is-directed-by-hidetaka-miyazaki/1100-6428145/|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=July 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723083419/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-is-directed-by-hidetaka-miyazaki/1100-6428145/|archivedate=July 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Scammell|first1=David|title=Dark Souls 3 is being developed by a different team to Bloodborne|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/dark_souls_3/news/dark_souls_3_is_being_developed_by_a_different_team_to_bloodborne.html|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617143650/http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/dark_souls_3/news/dark_souls_3_is_being_developed_by_a_different_team_to_bloodborne.html|archivedate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> After its release, Miyazaki stated his intentions to personally stop development on the ''Souls'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|title=Dark Souls 3 director already working on a new IP|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428104541/http://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|archivedate=April 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 Interview: \"It Wouldn\u2019t Be Right to Continue Creating Souls\"|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=March 26, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329130010/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|archivedate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> His next two projects were the 2018 [[virtual reality]] game ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]'' and the 2019 action-adventure game ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yamagiwa |first1=Masaaki |title=D\u00e9racin\u00e9: Japan Studio X FromSoftware's PS VR Debut |url=https://blog.us.playstation.com/2018/06/11/deracine-japan-studio-x-fromsoftwares-ps-vr-debut/ |website=blog.us.playstation.com |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141203/https://blog.us.playstation.com/2018/06/11/deracine-japan-studio-x-fromsoftwares-ps-vr-debut/ |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=FromSoftware's Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice coming from Activision |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141020/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> At the [[2018 Golden Joystick Awards]] ceremony, he was awarded the show's Lifetime Achievement Award for his contributions to the [[video game industry]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Lucas |title=Dark Souls creator Hidetaka Miyazaki takes the Lifetime Achievement award at the Golden Joystick Awards 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-creator-hidetaki-miyazaki-takes-the-lifetime-achievement-award-at-the-golden-joystick-awards-2018/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=November 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116214028/https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-creator-hidetaki-miyazaki-takes-the-lifetime-achievement-award-at-the-golden-joystick-awards-2018/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The award was presented to him by [[Ian Livingstone]] and [[Steve Jackson (British game designer)|Steve Jackson]], two of his design influences.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruppert |first1=Liana |title='Dark Souls' Creator Hidetaka Miyazaki Accepts Lifetime Achievement Award |url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/11/17/dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-lifetime-achievement-award/ |website=ComicBook.com |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128123008/https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/11/17/dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-lifetime-achievement-award/ |archive-date=November 28, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Miyazaki is also set to direct the action role-playing game ''[[Elden Ring]]'', written in collaboration with ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series author [[George R. R. Martin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Josh |title=Elden Ring had its 'overarching mythos' written by George RR Martin, reveals Hidetaka Miyazaki |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/elden-ring-had-its-overarching-mythos-written-by-george-rr-martin-reveals-hidetaka-miyazaki/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences and design philosophy==\n{{Multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| direction = horizontal\n| align = right\n| total_width = 400\n| footer = Miyazaki is often inspired by real world architecture and incorporates elements of them as [[Visual narrative|environmental storytelling]] in his games. One such example is [[Anor Londo]], a central location in ''Dark Souls'', being modeled after the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chambord]] (''left'') in France and [[Milan Cathedral]] (''right'') in Italy.\n| image1 = Escalier double helice Chambord.jpg\n| image2 = Milan_Cathedral_from_Piazza_del_Duomo.jpg\n}}\nMiyazaki's influences include video games such as ''[[Ico]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parkin|first1=Simon|title=Bloodborne creator Hidetaka Miyazaki: \u2018I didn\u2019t have a dream. I wasn\u2019t ambitious'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603192210/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> the early ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' games,<ref name=\"edge\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nunneley|first1=Stephany|title=Dark Souls online play to bring back the feeling of old Dragon Quest games|url=http://www.vg247.com/2011/02/08/dark-souls-online-play-to-bring-back-the-feeling-of-old-dragon-quest-games/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630185933/http://www.vg247.com/2011/02/08/dark-souls-online-play-to-bring-back-the-feeling-of-old-dragon-quest-games/|archivedate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|title=Dark Souls' grand vision |url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/dark-matters-0?page=2 |website=Edge |accessdate=July 13, 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204210941/http://www.edge-online.com/features/dark-matters-0?page=2 |archivedate=February 4, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|last1=Mielke|first1=James|title='Dark Souls' Creator Miyazaki on 'Zelda,' Sequels and Starting Out|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/dark-souls-creator-miyazaki-on-zelda-sequels-w443435|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=October 6, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005123700/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/dark-souls-creator-miyazaki-on-zelda-sequels-w443435|archivedate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[King's Field (series)|King's Field]]'' video game series,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Dave|title=From King's Field to Bloodborne: the lineage of Dark Souls|url=http://www.vg247.com/2014/07/02/from-kings-field-to-bloodborne-the-lineage-of-dark-souls/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415090716/http://www.vg247.com/2014/07/02/from-kings-field-to-bloodborne-the-lineage-of-dark-souls/|archivedate=April 15, 2015}}</ref> [[manga]] series such as ''[[Berserk (manga)|Berserk]]'', ''[[Saint Seiya]]'', ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Souls Design Works Translation: Weapons and Equipment Part 1/2|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/profile/7force/blog/dark-souls-design-works-translation-weapons-and-eq/99682/|publisher=[[Giant Bomb]]|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522081824/http://www.giantbomb.com/profile/7force/blog/dark-souls-design-works-translation-weapons-and-eq/99682/|archivedate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Devilman]]'',<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> the literary works of [[H. P. Lovecraft]], [[Bram Stoker]], and [[George R. R. Martin]],<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.eu.playstation.com/t5/Bloodborne/Bloodborne-Exclusive-Interview-with-Jun-Yoshino/td-p/23062300|title=[Bloodborne] Exclusive Interview with Jun Yoshino!|work=playstation.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415180918/http://community.eu.playstation.com/t5/Bloodborne/Bloodborne-Exclusive-Interview-with-Jun-Yoshino/td-p/23062300|archivedate=April 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Krabbe |first1=Esra |title=Elden Ring Is an Evolution of Dark Souls Says Creator \u2013 E3 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/21/elden-ring-is-an-evolution-of-dark-souls-says-creator-a-e3-2019 |website=IGN |accessdate=June 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622003421/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/21/elden-ring-is-an-evolution-of-dark-souls-says-creator-a-e3-2019 |archive-date=June 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[gamebook]]s such as ''[[Steve Jackson's Sorcery!]]'' and ''[[RuneQuest]]''.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 Interview: \"It Wouldn\u2019t Be Right to Continue Creating Souls\"|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=November 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122053418/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|archivedate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> Miyazaki is also inspired by [[architecture]], especially of Europe, and often uses it as a way of [[Visual narrative|environmental storytelling]].<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite web|last1=Kamen|first1=Matt|title=Dark Souls 3 director: it's about 'accomplishment by overcoming tremendous odds'|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2016-03/29/dark-souls-3-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|website=Wired|accessdate=April 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420002105/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2016-03/29/dark-souls-3-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=April 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McMullan|first1=Thomas|title=From Dark Souls to Manifold Garden: How games tell stories through architecture|url=http://www.alphr.com/games/1002937/from-dark-souls-to-manifold-garden-how-games-tell-stories-through-architecture|website=Alphr|accessdate=June 10, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616142304/http://www.alphr.com/games/1002937/from-dark-souls-to-manifold-garden-how-games-tell-stories-through-architecture|archivedate=June 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stanton|first1=Rich|title=The Real Dark Souls Starts Here: 13 Real-Life Inspirations for Lordran|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/03/13/the-real-dark-souls-starts-here-12-real-life-inspirations-for-lordran|website=IGN|accessdate=August 1, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820122045/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/03/13/the-real-dark-souls-starts-here-12-real-life-inspirations-for-lordran|archivedate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> He stated that [[psychology]], [[sociology]], and the [[history of humanity]] have also influenced his design philosophy.<ref name=\"IGNinterview\" /> \n\nThe multiplayer mechanics of the ''Souls'' series were inspired by his own personal experience of driving up on a snowy road as cars ahead began slipping back and were pushed up hill by other people in the area. As Miyazaki was unable to give his appreciation to them before leaving the area, he wondered whether the last person in the line had made it to their destination, thinking that he would probably never meet them again. This gave birth to the series' interconnected multiplayer systems, with it attempting to emulate that same sense of silent cooperation in the face of adversity.<ref name=\"SoulsSurvivor\">{{cite web|author=MacDonald, Keza|title=Souls Survivor|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/souls-survivor|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 27, 2010|accessdate=April 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319020959/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/souls-survivor|archivedate=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMiyazaki stated that the notable difficulty of the ''Souls'' series had no intention of being \"more difficult than other titles on purpose\". Rather, the difficulty was a part of the process that gives players \"a sense of accomplishment by overcoming tremendous odds\", while also having a certain level of difficulty incentivizing players to \"experiment more with character builds and weapon load-outs\".<ref name=\"Wired\"/> He has stated that death is supposed to be a tool meant to be used to learn in a trial and error process, and that the idea of using death in-game as an educational tool would have been received poorly by both his superiors and players, at least before the commercial and critical success of ''Demon's Souls''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/11/08/the-mind-behind-dark-souls|title=A journey into the mentality of Dark Souls with director Hidetaka Miyazaki.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426012350/http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/11/08/the-mind-behind-dark-souls|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nWhen asked about his style of storytelling, Miyazaki stated that despite what others may believe, he does not dislike direct storytelling, but instead prefers players to interpret the world for themselves; stating that the player gets more value from it when \"they themselves find out hints of plot from items or side-characters they encounter in the world\".<ref name=\"Wired\"/> Many gaming journalists and critics have called him an \"[[auteur]]\" of video games, noting his influential work in the ''Souls'' series that has gone on to influence other game designers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hosie |first1=Ewen |title=The Architects: Video Gaming's Auteurs |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/26/the-architects-video-gamings-auteurs |website=IGN |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hetfeld |first1=Malindy |title=Auteur Theory and Games |url=https://unwinnable.com/2018/08/20/auteur-theory-and-games/ |website=Unwinnable.com |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Avard |first1=Alex |title=Dark Souls + Game of Thrones anybody? George R.R. Martin and FromSoftware have apparently teamed up to work on a new game |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-game-of-thrones-anybody-george-rr-martin-and-fromsoftware-have-apparently-teamed-up-to-work-on-a-new-game/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"auto\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title !! Role\n|-\n! 2005\n| ''[[Armored Core: Last Raven]]'' || Planner\n|-\n! 2006\n| ''[[Armored Core 4]]'' || rowspan=\"3\" | Director\n|-\n! 2008\n| ''[[Armored Core: For Answer]]''\n|-\n! 2009\n| ''[[Demon's Souls]]''\n|-\n! 2011\n| ''[[Dark Souls]]'' || Director, producer\n|-\n! 2014\n| ''[[Dark Souls II]]'' || Supervisor\n|-\n! 2015\n| ''[[Bloodborne]]''|| rowspan=\"5\" | Director\n|-\n! 2016\n| ''[[Dark Souls III]]''\n|-\n! 2018\n| ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]''\n|-\n! 2019\n| ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''\n|-\n! TBA\n| ''[[Elden Ring]]''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|2329298}}\n\n{{FromSoftware}}\n{{Souls series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miyazaki, Hidetaka}}\n[[Category:Japanese chief executives]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game designers]]\n[[Category:Keio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Shizuoka (city)]]\n[[Category:Souls series]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game directors]]\n[[Category:Video game writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese video game director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hidetaka Miyazaki\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| native_name        = \u5bae\u5d0e \u82f1\u9ad8\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date|mos=1|29|2004}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka]], Japan\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| alma_mater         = [[Keio University]]\n| occupation         = [[Creative director|Game director]], [[game designer]], writer\n| notable_works      = {{ubl|''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series|''[[Bloodborne]]''|''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''}}\n| title              = [[President (corporate title)|President]] of [[FromSoftware|FromSoftware, Inc.]]\n| term               = 2014\u2013present\n| awards             = {{ubl|Lifetime Achievement|([[2018 Golden Joystick Awards]])}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Hidetaka Miyazaki'''|\u5bae\u5d0e \u82f1\u9ad8|Miyazaki Hidetaka|born in [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka]], Japan}} is a Japanese [[Creative director|video game director]], designer, writer, and company [[President (corporate title)|president]] of [[FromSoftware]]. He originally joined them in 2004 as a game designer for the ''[[Armored Core]]'' series, and soon became internationally known for directing the ''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series, starting with ''[[Demon's Souls]]'' in 2009. Other notable games he has directed include ''[[Bloodborne]]'' and ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.\n\nMiyazaki's influences range from the works of various novelists, [[mangaka]]s, and other [[game designer]]s such as [[Fumito Ueda]] and [[Yuji Horii]], as well as Asian and European architecture. Miyazaki's games, particularly the ''Souls'' series, often invoke the use of [[Degree of difficulty#In video gaming|high difficulty]], strong [[visual storytelling|visual and environmental storytelling]], and a large amount of [[Setting (narrative)|setting]] and character background information provided through mostly vague [[flavor text]] and [[Fluff (fiction)|fluff]]. His work in the ''Souls'' series has been seen as influential, with him winning awards and being cited as an [[auteur]] of video games.\n\n==Early life==\nMiyazaki grew up \"tremendously poor\" while living in the city of [[Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka, Japan]], stating that he had no life ambitions as a child unlike many peers at that age.<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Parkin|first1=Simon|title=Bloodborne creator Hidetaka Miyazaki: \u2018I didn\u2019t have a dream. I wasn\u2019t ambitious'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 8, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603192210/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> Despite that, he was a heavy reader, but as his parents could not afford to buy him books or [[manga]], he had to borrow from his local library.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> The books he read at the time, many in English, were sometimes beyond his reading capabilities, with parts he could not fully understand. Using his imagination to fill in the blanks by using the accompanying illustrations, Miyazaki used this as inspiration for some of his later ideas on [[video game design]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Alongside this, he was restricted from playing video games by his parents until he was old enough to attend university, so he instead played [[gamebook]]s and [[tabletop game]]s such as ''[[Steve Jackson's Sorcery!]]'' and ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.<ref name=\"IGNinterview\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from [[Keio University]] with a degree in [[social science]], Miyazaki went to work doing [[account managing]] for the US based [[Oracle Corporation]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/><ref name=\"andriasang\">{{cite web|last1=Gantayat|first1=Anoop|title=Hidetaka Miyazaki Discusses Dark Souls|url=http://andriasang.com/comttl/miyazaki_dark_souls/|accessdate=April 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427103144/http://andriasang.com/comttl/miyazaki_dark_souls/ |archivedate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Upon a friend's recommendation, Miyazaki began playing the 2001 video game ''[[Ico]]'', causing him to consider a career change to a game designer.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> At age 29 however, Miyazaki found that few game companies would employ him, with one of the few being [[FromSoftware]], where Miyazaki began working as a game planner on ''[[Armored Core: Last Raven]]'' in 2004, joining the game's development halfway through.<ref name=\"Interview\"/><ref name=\"andriasang\"/> Miyazaki later directed ''[[Armored Core 4]]'' and its direct sequel, ''[[Armored Core: For Answer]]''.<ref name=\"andriasang\"/>\n\nUpon learning about what later became ''[[Demon's Souls]]'', Miyazaki became excited at the prospect of a fantasy [[action role-playing game]] and offered to help.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> The project, up until Miyazaki was assigned to it, was considered a failure by the company, with Miyazaki stating \"I figured if I could find a way to take control of the game, I could turn it into anything I wanted. Best of all, if my ideas failed, nobody would care \u2013 it was already a failure.\"<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Although the game was received negatively at the 2009 [[Tokyo Game Show]] and sold far under expectations upon release, it began to pick up after a few months and soon found publishers willing to release the title outside of Japan.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> After the release and success of the game's [[spiritual successor]] ''[[Dark Souls]]'' in 2011, Miyazaki was promoted to the position of company president in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duwell|first1=Ron|title=Dark Souls\u2019 Hidetaka Miyazaki Promoted to President of From Software|url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/05/22/dark-souls-hidetaka-miyazaki-promoted-to-president-of-from-software/|publisher=Techno Buffalo|accessdate=March 25, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402192158/http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/05/22/dark-souls-hidetaka-miyazaki-promoted-to-president-of-from-software/|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Karmali|first1=Luke|title=Dark Souls Director Hidetaka Miyazaki Made President of From Software|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/21/dark-souls-director-hidetaka-miyazaki-made-from-software-president|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=June 10, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524103505/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/21/dark-souls-director-hidetaka-miyazaki-made-from-software-president|archivedate=May 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the release of the ''Prepare to Die'' edition of ''Dark Souls'' in August 2012, [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] approached FromSoftware concerning cooperative development on a new title. Miyazaki asked about the possibility of developing a game for [[History of video game consoles (eighth generation)|eighth-generation consoles]], and the concept of ''[[Bloodborne]]'' developed from there. There were no story or setting connections to FromSoftware's previous games, even though Miyazaki conceded that it carried the \"DNA\" of ''Demon's Souls'' and its specific level design.<ref name= \"IGNinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/02/05/inside-the-mind-of-bloodborne-and-dark-souls-creator-ign-first|title=Inside the Mind of Bloodborne and Dark Souls' Creator \u2013 IGN First|last=Silva|first=Marty|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=February 5, 2015|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref> Development ran parallel to that of ''Dark Souls II'', which Miyazaki supervised only as he was unable to direct both games simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/260/G026038/20140611091/|title=\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30cf\u30fc\u30c9\u3067\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u3092\u2015\u2015PS4\u5c02\u7528\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u300cBloodborne\uff08\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30c9\u30dc\u30fc\u30f3\uff09\u300d\u3068\u306f\u3069\u3093\u306a\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u306a\u306e\u304b\u3002\u30c7\u30a3\u30ec\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30fb\u5bae\u5d0e\u82f1\u9ad8\u6c0f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|language=Japanese|publisher=4Gamer|date=June 19, 2014|accessdate=February 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216122013/http://www.4gamer.net/games/260/G026038/20140611091/|archivedate=February 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the release of ''Bloodborne'' in March 2015, Miyazaki returned to the ''Souls'' series as the director on ''[[Dark Souls III]]'' (2016), with assistance from ''[[Steel Battalion: Heavy Armor]]'' and ''[[Dark Souls II]]'' directors Isamu Okano and Yui Tanimura, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 is Directed by Hidetaka Miyazaki|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-is-directed-by-hidetaka-miyazaki/1100-6428145/|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=July 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723083419/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-is-directed-by-hidetaka-miyazaki/1100-6428145/|archivedate=July 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Scammell|first1=David|title=Dark Souls 3 is being developed by a different team to Bloodborne|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/dark_souls_3/news/dark_souls_3_is_being_developed_by_a_different_team_to_bloodborne.html|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617143650/http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/dark_souls_3/news/dark_souls_3_is_being_developed_by_a_different_team_to_bloodborne.html|archivedate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> After its release, Miyazaki stated his intentions to personally stop development on the ''Souls'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|title=Dark Souls 3 director already working on a new IP|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428104541/http://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|archivedate=April 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 Interview: \"It Wouldn\u2019t Be Right to Continue Creating Souls\"|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=March 26, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329130010/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|archivedate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> His next two projects were the 2018 [[virtual reality]] game ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]'' and the 2019 action-adventure game ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yamagiwa |first1=Masaaki |title=D\u00e9racin\u00e9: Japan Studio X FromSoftware's PS VR Debut |url=https://blog.us.playstation.com/2018/06/11/deracine-japan-studio-x-fromsoftwares-ps-vr-debut/ |website=blog.us.playstation.com |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141203/https://blog.us.playstation.com/2018/06/11/deracine-japan-studio-x-fromsoftwares-ps-vr-debut/ |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=FromSoftware's Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice coming from Activision |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141020/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> At the [[2018 Golden Joystick Awards]] ceremony, he was awarded the show's Lifetime Achievement Award for his contributions to the [[video game industry]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Lucas |title=Dark Souls creator Hidetaka Miyazaki takes the Lifetime Achievement award at the Golden Joystick Awards 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-creator-hidetaki-miyazaki-takes-the-lifetime-achievement-award-at-the-golden-joystick-awards-2018/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=November 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116214028/https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-creator-hidetaki-miyazaki-takes-the-lifetime-achievement-award-at-the-golden-joystick-awards-2018/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The award was presented to him by [[Ian Livingstone]] and [[Steve Jackson (British game designer)|Steve Jackson]], two of his design influences.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruppert |first1=Liana |title='Dark Souls' Creator Hidetaka Miyazaki Accepts Lifetime Achievement Award |url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/11/17/dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-lifetime-achievement-award/ |website=ComicBook.com |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128123008/https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/11/17/dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-lifetime-achievement-award/ |archive-date=November 28, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Miyazaki is also set to direct the action role-playing game ''[[Elden Ring]]'', written in collaboration with ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series author [[George R. R. Martin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Josh |title=Elden Ring had its 'overarching mythos' written by George RR Martin, reveals Hidetaka Miyazaki |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/elden-ring-had-its-overarching-mythos-written-by-george-rr-martin-reveals-hidetaka-miyazaki/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences and design philosophy==\n{{Multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| direction = horizontal\n| align = right\n| total_width = 400\n| footer = Miyazaki is often inspired by real world architecture and incorporates elements of them as [[Visual narrative|environmental storytelling]] in his games. One such example is [[Anor Londo]], a central location in ''Dark Souls'', being modeled after the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chambord]] (''left'') in France and [[Milan Cathedral]] in Italy (''right'').\n| image1 = Escalier double helice Chambord.jpg\n| image2 = Milan_Cathedral_from_Piazza_del_Duomo.jpg\n}}\nMiyazaki's influences include video games such as ''[[Ico]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parkin|first1=Simon|title=Bloodborne creator Hidetaka Miyazaki: \u2018I didn\u2019t have a dream. I wasn\u2019t ambitious'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603192210/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/31/bloodborne-dark-souls-creator-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> the early ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' games,<ref name=\"edge\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nunneley|first1=Stephany|title=Dark Souls online play to bring back the feeling of old Dragon Quest games|url=http://www.vg247.com/2011/02/08/dark-souls-online-play-to-bring-back-the-feeling-of-old-dragon-quest-games/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630185933/http://www.vg247.com/2011/02/08/dark-souls-online-play-to-bring-back-the-feeling-of-old-dragon-quest-games/|archivedate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|title=Dark Souls' grand vision |url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/dark-matters-0?page=2 |website=Edge |accessdate=July 13, 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204210941/http://www.edge-online.com/features/dark-matters-0?page=2 |archivedate=February 4, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|last1=Mielke|first1=James|title='Dark Souls' Creator Miyazaki on 'Zelda,' Sequels and Starting Out|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/dark-souls-creator-miyazaki-on-zelda-sequels-w443435|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=October 6, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005123700/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/dark-souls-creator-miyazaki-on-zelda-sequels-w443435|archivedate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[King's Field (series)|King's Field]]'' video game series,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Dave|title=From King's Field to Bloodborne: the lineage of Dark Souls|url=http://www.vg247.com/2014/07/02/from-kings-field-to-bloodborne-the-lineage-of-dark-souls/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415090716/http://www.vg247.com/2014/07/02/from-kings-field-to-bloodborne-the-lineage-of-dark-souls/|archivedate=April 15, 2015}}</ref> [[manga]] series such as ''[[Berserk (manga)|Berserk]]'', ''[[Saint Seiya]]'', ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Souls Design Works Translation: Weapons and Equipment Part 1/2|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/profile/7force/blog/dark-souls-design-works-translation-weapons-and-eq/99682/|publisher=[[Giant Bomb]]|accessdate=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522081824/http://www.giantbomb.com/profile/7force/blog/dark-souls-design-works-translation-weapons-and-eq/99682/|archivedate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Devilman]]'',<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> the literary works of [[H. P. Lovecraft]], [[Bram Stoker]], and [[George R. R. Martin]],<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.eu.playstation.com/t5/Bloodborne/Bloodborne-Exclusive-Interview-with-Jun-Yoshino/td-p/23062300|title=[Bloodborne] Exclusive Interview with Jun Yoshino!|work=playstation.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415180918/http://community.eu.playstation.com/t5/Bloodborne/Bloodborne-Exclusive-Interview-with-Jun-Yoshino/td-p/23062300|archivedate=April 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Krabbe |first1=Esra |title=Elden Ring Is an Evolution of Dark Souls Says Creator \u2013 E3 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/21/elden-ring-is-an-evolution-of-dark-souls-says-creator-a-e3-2019 |website=IGN |accessdate=June 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622003421/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/21/elden-ring-is-an-evolution-of-dark-souls-says-creator-a-e3-2019 |archive-date=June 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[gamebook]]s such as ''[[Steve Jackson's Sorcery!]]'' and ''[[RuneQuest]]''.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Dark Souls 3 Interview: \"It Wouldn\u2019t Be Right to Continue Creating Souls\"|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=November 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122053418/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-3-interview-it-wouldnt-be-right-to-cont/1100-6432425/|archivedate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> Miyazaki is also inspired by [[architecture]], especially of Europe, and often uses it as a way of [[Visual narrative|environmental storytelling]].<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite web|last1=Kamen|first1=Matt|title=Dark Souls 3 director: it's about 'accomplishment by overcoming tremendous odds'|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2016-03/29/dark-souls-3-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|website=Wired|accessdate=April 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420002105/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2016-03/29/dark-souls-3-hidetaka-miyazaki-interview|archivedate=April 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McMullan|first1=Thomas|title=From Dark Souls to Manifold Garden: How games tell stories through architecture|url=http://www.alphr.com/games/1002937/from-dark-souls-to-manifold-garden-how-games-tell-stories-through-architecture|website=Alphr|accessdate=June 10, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616142304/http://www.alphr.com/games/1002937/from-dark-souls-to-manifold-garden-how-games-tell-stories-through-architecture|archivedate=June 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stanton|first1=Rich|title=The Real Dark Souls Starts Here: 13 Real-Life Inspirations for Lordran|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/03/13/the-real-dark-souls-starts-here-12-real-life-inspirations-for-lordran|website=IGN|accessdate=August 1, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820122045/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/03/13/the-real-dark-souls-starts-here-12-real-life-inspirations-for-lordran|archivedate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> He stated that [[psychology]], [[sociology]], and the [[history of humanity]] have also influenced his design philosophy.<ref name=\"IGNinterview\" /> \n\nThe multiplayer mechanics of the ''Souls'' series were inspired by his own personal experience of driving up on a snowy road as cars ahead began slipping back and were pushed up hill by other people in the area. As Miyazaki was unable to give his appreciation to them before leaving the area, he wondered whether the last person in the line had made it to their destination, thinking that he would probably never meet them again. This gave birth to the series' interconnected multiplayer systems, with it attempting to emulate that same sense of silent cooperation in the face of adversity.<ref name=\"SoulsSurvivor\">{{cite web|author=MacDonald, Keza|title=Souls Survivor|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/souls-survivor|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 27, 2010|accessdate=April 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319020959/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/souls-survivor|archivedate=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMiyazaki stated that the notable difficulty of the ''Souls'' series had no intention of being \"more difficult than other titles on purpose\". Rather, the difficulty was a part of the process that gives players \"a sense of accomplishment by overcoming tremendous odds\", while also having a certain level of difficulty incentivizing players to \"experiment more with character builds and weapon load-outs\".<ref name=\"Wired\"/> He has stated that death is supposed to be a tool meant to be used to learn in a trial and error process, and that the idea of using death in-game as an educational tool would have been received poorly by both his superiors and players, at least before the commercial and critical success of ''Demon's Souls''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/11/08/the-mind-behind-dark-souls|title=A journey into the mentality of Dark Souls with director Hidetaka Miyazaki.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426012350/http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/11/08/the-mind-behind-dark-souls|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nWhen asked about his style of storytelling, Miyazaki stated that despite what others may believe, he does not dislike direct storytelling, but instead prefers players to interpret the world for themselves; stating that the player gets more value from it when \"they themselves find out hints of plot from items or side-characters they encounter in the world\".<ref name=\"Wired\"/> Many gaming journalists and critics have called him an \"[[auteur]]\" of video games, noting his influential work in the ''Souls'' series that has gone on to influence other game designers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hosie |first1=Ewen |title=The Architects: Video Gaming's Auteurs |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/26/the-architects-video-gamings-auteurs |website=IGN |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hetfeld |first1=Malindy |title=Auteur Theory and Games |url=https://unwinnable.com/2018/08/20/auteur-theory-and-games/ |website=Unwinnable.com |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Avard |first1=Alex |title=Dark Souls + Game of Thrones anybody? George R.R. Martin and FromSoftware have apparently teamed up to work on a new game |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/dark-souls-game-of-thrones-anybody-george-rr-martin-and-fromsoftware-have-apparently-teamed-up-to-work-on-a-new-game/ |website=GamesRadar+ |accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"auto\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title !! Role\n|-\n! 2005\n| ''[[Armored Core: Last Raven]]'' || Planner\n|-\n! 2006\n| ''[[Armored Core 4]]'' || rowspan=\"3\" | Director\n|-\n! 2008\n| ''[[Armored Core: For Answer]]''\n|-\n! 2009\n| ''[[Demon's Souls]]''\n|-\n! 2011\n| ''[[Dark Souls]]'' || Director, producer\n|-\n! 2014\n| ''[[Dark Souls II]]'' || Supervisor\n|-\n! 2015\n| ''[[Bloodborne]]''|| rowspan=\"5\" | Director\n|-\n! 2016\n| ''[[Dark Souls III]]''\n|-\n! 2018\n| ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]''\n|-\n! 2019\n| ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''\n|-\n! TBA\n| ''[[Elden Ring]]''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|2329298}}\n\n{{FromSoftware}}\n{{Souls series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miyazaki, Hidetaka}}\n[[Category:Japanese chief executives]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game designers]]\n[[Category:Keio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Shizuoka (city)]]\n[[Category:Souls series]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game directors]]\n[[Category:Video game writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Japanese video game businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Dissident93", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfluences and design philosophy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hidetaka_Miyazaki"}
{"title_page": "Jerry Slijngard", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jerry Slijngard\n| image         = Jerry Slijngard (cropped).jpg\n| alt           = Jerry Slijngard\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Suriname]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Director Coast Guard <br> Director National Coordination Centre for Emergency Management (NCCR)\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Jerry Slingard''' is a [[Surinamese people|Surinamese]] soldier and official. Jerry Slingard has the rank of [[ colonel]]. In 2003 he was appointed to head the National Coordination Centre for Emergency Management (NCCR). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parbode.com/klaar-voor-de-ramp/|title=Ready for the disaster (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Parbode}}</ref>\nIn 2013 he was appointed to head the newly created [[Coast Guard]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/17870|title=Slijngaard: Boat first visible result Coast Guard (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Star Nieuws}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gov.sr/themas/veiligheid-en-orde/kustwacht/|title=Coast Guard (in Dutch)|website=gov.sr|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Corona epidemic==\nAt the announcement of the first Covid-19 infection in Suriname, Slijngard was appointed  as a member of the National COVID-19 Managementteam which coordinates the fight against the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Suriname|Coronavirus pandemic]] in Suriname. After [[Antoine Joly]], the [[France|French]] ambassador to Suriname, tested positive on 24 April 2020, <ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> [[Danielle Veira]], the Director of the COVID-19 Managementteam, went into quarantine, and <ref name=\"quarantine\">{{Cite news|url=https://fathh.com/suriname/nieuws/118007/franse-ambassadeur-8ste-covid-19-slachtoffer.html|title=France Ambassador 8th Covid 19 victim (in Dutch)|website=Suriname News|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jerry Slijgard was temporarily appointed as her successor. <ref name=\"quarantine\"/> Veira  returned to resume her duties on 2 April 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.srherald.com/suriname/2020/04/02/dnv-directeur-veira-uit-quarantaine/|title=Director DNV Veira out of quarantine|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Suriname Herald}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slijngard, Jerry}}\n{{Suriname-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Surinamese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jerry Slijngard\n| image         = Jerry Slijngard (cropped).jpg\n| alt           = Jerry Slijngard\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Suriname]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Director Coast Guard <br> Director National Coordination Centre for Emergency Management (NCCR)\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Jerry Slingard''' is a [[Surinamese people|Surinamese]] soldier and official. Jerry Slingard has the rank of [[ colonel]]. In 2003 he was appointed to head the National Coordination Centre for Emergency Management (NCCR). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parbode.com/klaar-voor-de-ramp/|title=Ready for the disaster (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Parbode}}</ref>\nIn 2013 he was appointed to head the newly created [[Coast Guard]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/17870|title=Slijngaard: Boat first visible result Coast Guard (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Star Nieuws}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gov.sr/themas/veiligheid-en-orde/kustwacht/|title=Coast Guard (in Dutch)|website=gov.sr|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Corona epidemic==\nAt the announcement of the first Covid-19 infection in Suriname, Slijngard was appointed  as a member of the National COVID-19 Managementteam which coordinates the fight against the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Suriname|Coronavirus pandemic]] in Suriname. After [[Antoine Joly]], the [[France|French]] ambassador to Suriname, tested positive on 24 April 2020, <ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital (in Dutch)|access-date=4 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> [[Danielle Veira]], the Director of the COVID-19 Managementteam, went into quarantine, and <ref name=\"quarantine\">{{Cite news|url=https://fathh.com/suriname/nieuws/118007/franse-ambassadeur-8ste-covid-19-slachtoffer.html|title=France Ambassador 8th Covid 19 victim (in Dutch)|website=Suriname News|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jerry Slijgard was temporarily appointed as her successor. <ref name=\"quarantine\"/> Veira  returned to resume her duties on 2 April 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.srherald.com/suriname/2020/04/02/dnv-directeur-veira-uit-quarantaine/|title=Director DNV Veira out of quarantine|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Suriname Herald}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slijngard, Jerry}}\n{{Suriname-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Surinamese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy pasta error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Slijngard"}
{"title_page": "Knightly Chetwood", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n\n'''Knightly Chetwood''' (also '''Knightley Chetwood''') (b [[Chetwode]] 1650; d [[Tempsford]] to 1720) was an [[Anglican]] [[priest]]<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/16689852 Trove]</ref> in the early 18th century.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Chetwood, Knightly|volume=10}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChetwood was the eldest son of Valentine Chetwood of Chetwood, [[ Buckinghamshire ]] and his wife Mary Shute, daughter of Francis Shute of [[Upton, Leicestershire]].  His younger brother [[Benjamin Chetwood]] moved to Ireland, where he sat in the [[Irish House of Commons]], and made an advantageous marriage to one of the co-heiresses of the Eustace family of Harristown.  \n\nHe was  [[baptised ]]  on 29 October 1650. He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]]. He was ordained a [[priest]] in [[London]] on 4 March 1683.\n\nHe held the [[Living (Christianity)|living]] at [[Great Rissington]]. He became [[Archdeacon of York]]<ref>\"The History and Antiquities of Gloucester: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time\" Rudge,T p256: Gloucester; Hough & Pace; 1811</ref> by Thomas Rudge on 10 January 1689.\n \nHe was the [[Dean of Gloucester]] from 1707<ref>[[s:Page:Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 body of work.djvu/486|Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 p444]]</ref> until his death on 4 April 1720.<ref>[[s:Page:Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 body of work.djvu/487|Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 p445]]</ref>\n\n==Works==\nChetwood's works are:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* ''A Life of Wentworth Dillon, earl of Roscommon'', in Baker MS. xxxvi. 27\u201344, on [[Wentworth Dillon, 4th Earl of Roscommon]]. It was summarised in a paper by [[Thompson Cooper]] in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' for December 1855. \n* ''Life of Lycurgus'', in the translation of ''[[Plutarch's Lives]]'' of 1683. \n* ''A Character, by a Person of Honour here in England'', prefixed to [[Saint Evremont]]'s ''Miscellaneous Essays, translated out of French and continued by Mr. Dryden'', 1692. \n* Life of [[Virgil]] and the Preface to the Pastorals in Dryden's translation of Virgil's Works, 1697. \n* Translation of the Second Philippic in ''Several Orations of Demosthenes, English'd from the Greek by several Hands'', 1702. \n* Three single sermons; also a \"Speech in the Lower House of Convocation on Friday, 20 May 1715. Against the late Riots\", Lond. 1715.\n* English poems, some of which are printed in Dryden's ''Miscellany'' and in Nichols's ''Select Collection of Poems''; also English and Latin verses on the death of the Duchess of Newcastle (1676), in the Cambridge University collection on the marriage of the Prince of Orange (1677), and before Lord Roscommon's ''Essay on Translated Verse'', 1685.\n\nHe also edited the ''Traitt\u00e9 touchant l'Obeissance Passive'', Lond. (1685), translated by the Earl of Roscommon from the English of [[William Sherlock]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nChetwood married a daughter of Samuel Shute, sheriff of London, and left a son and a daughter, both of whom died unmarried. The son, Dr. John Chetwood, fellow of [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], died 17 February 1752. His will dated 25 Sept. 1733, gave to Wadham Knatchbull, a fellow of the college, a legacy, a locket of Lord Roscommon's hair, and his books, with his late father's manuscript sermons, requesting that Knatchbull, by his will, would order them to be destroyed. Chetwood had a claim, vainly prosecuted by his son, to the ancient English barony of Wahull.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Chetwood, Knightly|volume=10}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[William Jane]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Dean of Gloucester]]|years=1707\u20131720}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Waugh (bishop)|John Waugh]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of York}}\n{{Deans of Gloucester}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chetwood, Knightley}}\n[[Category:People from Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:17th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:18th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Deans of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of York]]\n[[Category:1720 deaths]]\n[[Category:1650 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n\n'''Knightly Chetwood''' (also '''Knightley Chetwood''') (b [[Chetwode]] 1650; d [[Tempsford]] to 1720) was an [[Anglican]] [[priest]]<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/16689852 Trove]</ref> in the early 18th century.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Chetwood, Knightly|volume=10}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChetwood was the eldest son of Valentine Chetwood of Chetwood, [[ Buckinghamshire ]] and his wife Mary Shute, daughter of Francis Shute of [[Upton, Leicestershire]].  His younger brother [[Benjamin Chetwood]] moved to Ireland, where he sat in the [[Irish House of Commons]], and made an advantageous marriage to one of the co-heiresses of the Eustace family..  \n\nHe was  [[baptised ]]  on 29 October 1650. He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]]. He was ordained a [[priest]] in [[London]] on 4 March 1683.\n\nHe held the [[Living (Christianity)|living]] at [[Great Rissington]]. He became [[Archdeacon of York]]<ref>\"The History and Antiquities of Gloucester: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time\" Rudge,T p256: Gloucester; Hough & Pace; 1811</ref> by Thomas Rudge on 10 January 1689.\n \nHe was the [[Dean of Gloucester]] from 1707<ref>[[s:Page:Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 body of work.djvu/486|Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 p444]]</ref> until his death on 4 April 1720.<ref>[[s:Page:Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 body of work.djvu/487|Fasti ecclesiae Anglicanae Vol.1 p445]]</ref>\n\n==Works==\nChetwood's works are:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* ''A Life of Wentworth Dillon, earl of Roscommon'', in Baker MS. xxxvi. 27\u201344, on [[Wentworth Dillon, 4th Earl of Roscommon]]. It was summarised in a paper by [[Thompson Cooper]] in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' for December 1855. \n* ''Life of Lycurgus'', in the translation of ''[[Plutarch's Lives]]'' of 1683. \n* ''A Character, by a Person of Honour here in England'', prefixed to [[Saint Evremont]]'s ''Miscellaneous Essays, translated out of French and continued by Mr. Dryden'', 1692. \n* Life of [[Virgil]] and the Preface to the Pastorals in Dryden's translation of Virgil's Works, 1697. \n* Translation of the Second Philippic in ''Several Orations of Demosthenes, English'd from the Greek by several Hands'', 1702. \n* Three single sermons; also a \"Speech in the Lower House of Convocation on Friday, 20 May 1715. Against the late Riots\", Lond. 1715.\n* English poems, some of which are printed in Dryden's ''Miscellany'' and in Nichols's ''Select Collection of Poems''; also English and Latin verses on the death of the Duchess of Newcastle (1676), in the Cambridge University collection on the marriage of the Prince of Orange (1677), and before Lord Roscommon's ''Essay on Translated Verse'', 1685.\n\nHe also edited the ''Traitt\u00e9 touchant l'Obeissance Passive'', Lond. (1685), translated by the Earl of Roscommon from the English of [[William Sherlock]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nChetwood married a daughter of Samuel Shute, sheriff of London, and left a son and a daughter, both of whom died unmarried. The son, Dr. John Chetwood, fellow of [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], died 17 February 1752. His will dated 25 Sept. 1733, gave to Wadham Knatchbull, a fellow of the college, a legacy, a locket of Lord Roscommon's hair, and his books, with his late father's manuscript sermons, requesting that Knatchbull, by his will, would order them to be destroyed. Chetwood had a claim, vainly prosecuted by his son, to the ancient English barony of Wahull.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Chetwood, Knightly|volume=10}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[William Jane]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Dean of Gloucester]]|years=1707\u20131720}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Waugh (bishop)|John Waugh]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of York}}\n{{Deans of Gloucester}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chetwood, Knightley}}\n[[Category:People from Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:17th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:18th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Deans of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of York]]\n[[Category:1720 deaths]]\n[[Category:1650 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chrisdoyleorwell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knightly_Chetwood"}
{"title_page": "2015 World Men's Handball Championship \u2013 European qualification", "text_new": "The '''European qualification''' for the '''[[2015 World Men's Handball Championship]]''', in [[Qatar]], was disputed in two rounds among the teams that did not qualify for the [[2014 European Men's Handball Championship]] and the 12 teams that placed outside of the European Championship's top three (excluding [[Spain national handball team|Spain]], which were qualified automatically for the World Championship as holders).\n\nIn the first round of qualification, 20 teams not participating at the European Championship were split into five groups; the group winners advanced to the second round, joining the 12 European finalists and [[Germany national handball team|Germany]], which was given a [[bye (sports)|bye]] to this round. These 18 teams then were paired to play a two-legged playoff tie to determine the nine remaining World Championship qualifiers from Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurohandball.com/article/017302/Procedure+for+2015+World+Championship+Qualification+Europe|title=Procedure for 2015 World Championship Qualification Europe approved|date=2013-06-21|work=eurohandball.com|accessdate=2013-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurohandball.com/article/017308/Draw+procedure+for+first+phase+of+2015+World+Championship+Qualification+Europe+released|title=Draw procedure for first phase of 2015 World Championship Qualification Europe released|date=2013-06-24|work=eurohandball.com|accessdate=2013-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Group stage==\nThe draw was held on 27 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurohandball.com/article/17333|title=20 teams vie for a spot at 2015 World Championship Play-Offs Europe|date=2013-06-27|work=eurohandball.com|accessdate=2013-06-27}}</ref> The group winners advanced to the playoff round.\n\n===Group 1===\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|winpoints=2\n|show_positions=n\n\n|team1=LTU|name_LTU={{hb|LTU}}\